<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-532-831  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 532 831.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Oct 16 1990 v4 n35 p26(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Coastal Associates Publishing L.P. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Mac lends helping hand at Johns Hopkins lab. (BehavioralPharmacology Research Unit of Johns Hopkins School of Medicineuses Apple Macintosh microcomputer)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Kay, Emily.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>The Behavioral Pharmacology Research Unit of the Johns HopkinsSchool of Medicine uses Apple Macintosh microcomputers to reducecosts by automating various research procedures.andP;  UtilizingMacintosh graphics software packages, such as MacDraw and CricketGraph, has allowed the lab to eliminate two full-time positions.andO;SPSS Inc's SPSS for the Macintosh statistics package enables themainframe-based software to run on the Macintosh and saves thegroup the money formerly spent on mainframe computing time.andO;Additionally, it is more convenient for the research group to beable to do its computing on-site.andP;  A network of Macintoshesconnects counseling staff to a client-information database whichis also used by the pharmacy to generate medication orders.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Apple Computer Inc. (Products).andO;Ticker:    AAPL.andO;Product:   Apple Macintosh (Microcomputer) (Usage)SPSS for the Macintosh (Statistical software) (Usage).andO;Topic:     Cost ReductionEfficiencyNetworksRecords ManagementAutomationData AnalysisJohns Hopkins University. School of Medicine.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Saves money, speeds jobs, aids efficiencyandM;By Emily KayandM;Baltimore -- Paper and pencils are out -- so are people, in some cases -- andMacs are definitely in at the Behavioral Pharmacology Research Unit of theJohns Hopkins University School of Medicine here.andM;John Yingling, technical director of Hopkins' drug-use/abuse research group,credits the Mac with automating the unit's procedures.andM;In 1986 Yingling set up a network that allowed the counseling staff to enterbasic client-record information in a multi-user database, which the pharmacystaff used to generate daily medication orders.andP;  The nursing staff used theMac to log in data about dispensing medication.andM;&quot;If we could do what we did with this project, we felt that just aboutanything in the lab could be applied to some kind of networking idea,&quot;Yingling recalled.andM;Today, BPRU uses the Mac to dramatically reduce research staffers' work,increase efficiency and cut costs, Yingling said.andP;  BPRU interviews hundredsof clients at scheduled intervals and keeps updated data about them.andM;&quot;There are six self-administered questionnaires we use in the lab.andP;  A stafferqueues up the program and goes away.&quot;andM;BPRU also has found that the availability on the Mac of the mainframe-basedstatistics package, SPSS for the Macintosh from SPSS Inc., has led toconsiderable savings, Yingling noted.andM;An SPSS package costs more than $1,000, but Yingling said he believes he hassaved that much in mainframe computing time in the first couple of months ofuse.andM;&quot;It has allowed us to shift our focus of data analysis from the mainframeenvironment.andP;  Now we can do about 90 percent of those statisticalrequirements on-site.&quot;andM;Mac graphics software has enabled BPRU to eliminate the need for two graphicssupport positions, saving some $50,000 per year in full-time salaries.andP;  UsingComputer Associates Inc.'s Cricket Graph and Claris Corp.'s MacDraw, BPRUstaff can produce graphics suitable for scientific journals.andM;In addition, the Mac's interface has cut down on the need for formal stafftraining, ideal in an environment that fosters high turnover among researchassistants fresh out of college, said Herbert K. Lodder, director of thepsychiatry and behavioral sciences department.andM;&quot;Macs enabled us to do things we couldn't have gotten done and to stretchbucks that weren't there,&quot; Lodder said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>